data.text: @RoyalTrioUpdate @CamillaTominey Water births I heard are easier! Make sure they bring anesthesia
@RoyalTrioUpdate @CamillaTominey We praying for you please keep us posted of how you doing.
@RoyalTrioUpdate @CamillaTominey It's a woman's choice. But on balance as long as sufficient expertise is available in the event of an emergency. So probably cheaper to have it in hospital.
@RoyalTrioUpdate There is going to be a contingency plan basically for everywhere she is going to be. Be it Buckleberry, London, Norfolk or even Norway and Sweden.
@skippyboousa Anmer Hall is only included if she were to go into labour while in Norfolk during a weekend break or something like that.

@RoyalTrioUpdate No way do I see baby born in Norfolk on purpose. G&C’s schools are in London, doctors in London. Phillip had to go to Cambridge when he got sick at Sandringham. Safer at St Mary’s. Restrict fans, press from camping out until admitted.

@allthingsroyal @RoyalTrioUpdate @CamillaTominey I wouldn't be as glad... I think the hospital is the place one should give birth, just for the safety of mother and baby. I wouldn't be alive if my mum had stayed at home. And btw, I'm still excited for the baby. I was excited too for the birth of princess Ariane (WA/Max's 3rd)

@RoyalTrioUpdate @CamillaTominey I would be glad if she did. The madness at the hospital and the staring at doors has to stop. With George I understood the excitement and got in the excitement as well. But the third time? No.
